message:

using `System.exit` will prevent the activity from performing a clean
shutdown, i.e. properly destroying the activity, etc.

because `eventBus` had yet to be instantiated, i.e. additional checks
are needed to allow for a clean shutdown.

title: convert ProjectRepository to use Optional
message:
convert ProjectRepository to use Optional

instead of expecting `null` as the absence of a value, `Optional` should
be used which "forces" explicit checks for the presence of a value.

only instances where the absence of a valid return value is `null` is
affected, methods returning collections can return an empty collection.

move throttle from adapter to view model

instead of throttling the all events from the adapter, each event type
(clock in/out) should be independently throttled to prevent sending
duplicated events. this can easily be done from within the view model.

title: inject database into provider using Dagger
message:
inject database into provider using Dagger

to enable testing with another database, e.g. in-memory database, the
instance have to be injected with Dagger.

due to an implementation detail of the start up process this injection
have to be done "on demand", the application have not been created when
the provider is initialized.

and, since the provider is called from different threads the calls have
to be syncronized.

title: use days since unix epoch as timesheet group id
message:
use days since unix epoch as timesheet group id

version 0.10.2 of the advancedrecyclerview library introduced an
intentional breaking change in regards to how both view type and
group/child ids.

previous versions allowed usage of large ids, which is incorrect since
the value is separated into four segments (child/group id, view type,
and one reserved bit).

since each group in the timesheet represent a single day, the number of
days since unix epoch can be used as the id.

ref: https://github.com/h6ah4i/android-advancedrecyclerview/issues/321

title: Merge branch 'presenter-view-operations'
message:
Merge branch 'presenter-view-operations'

* presenter-view-operations:
  fetch data from view using strong reference
  perform actions with view using strong reference

title: fetch data from view using strong reference
message:
fetch data from view using strong reference

the pattern used to get data from the view is as follows, check that
the view is still attached and then attempt to fetch the data.

since the view is stored in a `WeakReference`, and the attached check
and data fetch are not performed against an explicit strong reference,
the actual view reference might have been released between the calls.

instead of checking whether the view is still attached using the weak
reference, a strong reference should be used.

and, to reduce the needed boilerplate and duplication, the action should
be passed as a lambda which only gets called if the view is attached.

one downside of using lambdas, at least in the current configuration, is
the number of additional methods generated.

since the `getView` method is no longer used outside of the class it can
be made private. and, the `isViewDetached` can be removed since it's no
longer being used.

title: perform actions with view using strong reference
message:
perform actions with view using strong reference

the pattern used to perform actions with the view is as follows, check
that the view is still attached and then perform the action.

since the view is stored in a `WeakReference`, and the attached check
and action are not performed against an explicit strong reference, the
actual view reference might have been released between the calls.

instead of checking whether the view is still attached using the weak
reference, a strong reference should be used.

and, to reduce the needed boilerplate and duplication, the action should
be passed as a lambda which only gets called if the view is attached.

one downside of using lambdas, at least in the current configuration, is
the number of additional methods generated.

to prevent issues, or violate domain logic, the `ClockActivityChange`

project state before clock out.

title: depend on ClockIn use case in ClockActivityChange
message:
depend on ClockIn use case in ClockActivityChange

if the user accidentally double tap the clock activity change toggle
(when the project is inactive), two new separate active time entries
are created.

this will cause the project to register double time. i.e. when pausing
and then resuming the project, the start time for the second interval
will be the same as the first interval.

this is caused due to the fact that the `ClockActivityChange` depend on
the project state from the presentation layer, and not the actual state
from the data store.

the `ClockActivityChange` should depend on the `ClockIn` use case, which
will enforce valid project state before clock in.

message:
move ClockActivityChange unit test instantiation

since there is no variation in instantiating the `ClockActivityChange`,
it can be done once in the `setUp` method (as opposed to instantiation
in each of the test methods).

title: suppress notification errors from invalid project state
message:
suppress notification errors from invalid project state

in, what seems like, random occurrences the pause and resume services
are called with a project that's in an invalid state for the called
service.

i.e. the pause service is called with an inactive project and the resume
service is called with an already active project.

from what i can tell, the user action of pausing or resuming a project
is performed and then the dismissed notification is displayed again,
with the now invalid project state.

since the internal behaviour is correct, in respect to the user action,
the state error can/should be suppressed pending more data.

specific exception should be used to enable the caller to distinguish
between different exception states.

title: throw specific exception when clock out failed

throw specific exception when clock out failed

when calling the `ClockOut` use case with an inactive project, a more
specific exception should be used to enable the caller to distinguish
between different exception states.

message:
only install leakcanary when not unit testing

installing leakcanary causes the robolectric unit tests to throw a
`NullPointerException` when running from within android studio
(running from the command-line seem fine).

as a, hopefully temporary, work-around the leakcanary installation
is excluded when running the unit tests.

ref:
https://github.com/square/leakcanary/issues/143#issuecomment-104677981

message: update version for leakcanary

message:
mark ProjectsModelResourceTest as abstract

since the `ProjectsModelResourceTest` is not supposed to contain any
test methods it should be marked as abstract to avoid confusion.

title: post ongoing notifications via service on start
message:
post ongoing notifications via service on start

posting the ongoing notifications while getting the project causes the
notification to behave erratic when pausing a project via the ongoing
notification (timing issue).

basic execution flow is as follows:
1. pause action sends an event to update the user interface
2. resume notification is sent (if ongoing notification is enabled)

since commit `dc1a904e3ffe606d4f4718f7bdf389971764ae01` the event to the
user interface will also cancel and re-post ongoing notifications.

this change was made to ensure that ongoing notifications are always
available on application start, e.g. if the device have been rebooted.

by moving the posting of ongoing notifications to a background service,
which gets called on application start, the behaviour returns to normal.

but it's a lot better/cleaner and easier to test.

`android.defaultConfig.versionName` should use the name of the tag.

the format for the previous tags and version names differ in that the
tags have the 'v'-prefix. since the version name is used in the Google
Play Store, the format for tags should adapt to the version name.

message:

`android.defaultConfig.versionCode` represent number of releases and can
be calculated from the number of tags.

this implementation will produce issues when rebuilding older versions
since the number of tags will be counted from master.

test view interactions for refreshing projects

since an interval is used to refresh the active projects, the test needs
to simulate intervals (i.e. use `TestScheduler` to pass the time).

title: use desired scheduler for refreshing projects
message:
use desired scheduler for refreshing projects

the default scheduler for the `interval`-operator is `computation` but
the subscription for refreshing active projects is using `newThread`.

this causes issues when testing due to the fact that two schedulers are
involved in the interval (not actively but initially).

instead of using the default scheduler and later replacing it with the
`newThread`, the desired scheduler should be used with the method-call.

correct ui issue when removing multiple items

when the user removes multiple items the user-interface will fail to
properly update, if the items are selected in a random order.

to correct the issue the items have be sorted before removal, this will
require the entire list of selected items.

also, the items have to be sorted in the reverse order (to remove items
from the bottom up), since removing an item will cause the indexes for
the following items to change.

title: hide TimeInAdapterResult constructor
message:
hide TimeInAdapterResult constructor

instead of using the constructor to create the TimeInAdapaterResult,
either of the static factory methods should be used.

title: allow for selecting multiple items
message:
allow for selecting multiple items

to allow the user to easier either register or remove items, support for
selecting multiple items is required.

the modification to the timesheet is not performed within a transaction,
meaning that the action is not guaranteed to either succeed or rollback
in the case of failure.

title: refine behaviour of long click
message:
refine behaviour of long click

to allow for a more consistent selection behaviour, the long click have
to be refined. a long click should no longer reselect an item, instead
it should only be used to activate the selection (with an initial item).

a tap should be used to either reselect or deselect an item.

title: allow for deselecting an item
message: allow for deselecting an item

title: simplify item selection
message: simplify item selection

title: clean up the timesheet selection interface
message: clean up the timesheet selection interface

title: get selected item from the adapter
message:
get selected item from the adapter

instead of sending the selected item to the fragment, the fragment
should ask the adapter when it needs the item. this would allow the
adapter to better encapsulate the selection state.

title: move view selection to the adapter
message:
move view selection to the adapter

the fragment should not keep track of the internal state of the adapter,
i.e. the selected items, this behaviour should be within the adapter.

also, when selecting an item, scrolled the item off-screen and scrolled
back, the correct item might not be visually selected. the correct item
would still be registered or removed, but the list selection would be
displayed incorrectly.

by keeping an internal set of the selected item(s) and checking wether
an item is contained within the set, the selection is a lot easier.

also, this approach simplifies adding support for multi-select.

title: remove usage of ListFragment from ProjectsView
message:
remove usage of ListFragment from ProjectsView

the `ListFragment` acts as a delegate between the presenter and adapter,
it reveals to much details of the fragments underlying data structure.

the coupling between the presenter and adapter have to be separate. the
details of the data structure have to be hidden, only the details that
are needed should be made visible.

since the presenter is using the `ListFragment` methods, these have to
be replaced with new methods.

the `ListFragment` inheritance have been removed, which allows for the
removal unnecessary boilerplate code.

the `ListFragment` have been marked as deprecated to avoid unnecessary
coupling in the future.

redundant test methods and excessive use of mocking have been removed to
clean up the unit tests (mocks are still used where it's required).

the test case have been migrated to use a data provider, instead of the
standard JUnit runner, to allow easier testing of methods with multiple
variations (e.g. calculations).

also, the construction of the Project have been refactored to use the
`Project.Builder` instead of `new Project(...)`.

title: throw checked exception for domain rule violation
message:
throw checked exception for domain rule violation

the `EntityMapper` allow transformation to throw `DomainException`, i.e.
domain rule violations should not throw runtime exceptions.

title: separate the purpose of `EntityMapper`
message:
separate the purpose of `EntityMapper`

mapping from one data source to domain entity must be allowed to throw
`DomainException` since the data might violate domain rules.

however, mapping from domain entity to another data source should not
have this restriction (it might have others in the future).

the purpose of the `EntityMapper` have been separated into two separate
interfaces, `EntityMapper` and `DataMapper`.

`EntityMapper` should transform to domain entity, and `DataMapper`
should transform from domain entity.

documentation have been updated for the related interfaces/classes.

title: Simplify working with permissions
message:
Simplify working with permissions

To reduce code duplication and increase readability common patterns for
working with permissions should be refactored into helper class.

title: Request write permission to external storage
message:
Request write permission to external storage

To allow users to backup data, we need permission to write to the
external storage.

By displaying a permission notification and allowing the user to
initiate the permission request, we can backup data.

If permission have been denied, we should accept this and not display
the message again until the user attempts another backup.

title: Only backup if permission is granted
message:
Only backup if permission is granted

If permission have not been granted to write to the external storage,
attempts to backup will always throw an exception.

To avoid thrown exceptions we should always check permission before
attempting to backup data.

title: Request read permission to external storage
message:
Request read permission to external storage

To allow users to restore the backups we need to be able to check if
any backups are available.

By displaying a permission notification and allowing the user to
initiate the permission request, we can check available backups.

There is no need to do additional permission checks when running the
restore, since the action is disabled if permission have been denied.

title: Refactor initiate backup/restore actions
message:
Refactor initiate backup/restore actions

Since the backup and restore actions require different permissions the
implementation for initiating the actions have to be separated.

By separating the code into separate methods the request permission
will be easier to handle for each separate action.

title: Only check backups if permission is granted
message:
Only check backups if permission is granted

If permission have not been granted to read the external storage,
attempts to check available backups will always throw an exception.

To avoid thrown exception we should always check permission before
attempting to check available backups.

title: Use try-with-resource when copying files
message:
Use try-with-resource when copying files

Since we have moved up to Java 7, we can clean up the code for copying
files by using try-with-resource.

Merge branch 'timesheet-filter'

* timesheet-filter:
  Remove item when registered based on preference
  Refresh timesheet when hide preference is changed
  Read/write hide preference for registered time
  Add a new menu for the `ProjectActivity`
  Rename the menu for timesheet actions

title: Remove item when registered based on preference
message:
Remove item when registered based on preference

To be consistent with the hide registered time behaviour, when marking
a new item as registered it should be removed rather than updated.

title: Refresh timesheet when hide preference is changed
message:
Refresh timesheet when hide preference is changed

To give the user direct feedback about the hide preference change, the
view have to refresh, i.e. reload the data.

When the 'Hide registered' menu item is checked/unchecked the view
`refresh`-method will clear the data and initiate a new load.

To avoid possible `NullPointerException`, the creation of the timesheet
fragment have been refactored into a getter method. The getter method
will create the fragment when needed.

title: Read/write hide preference for registered time
message:
Read/write hide preference for registered time

To enable the user to hide/show registered time, we have to store the
selected preference in a global container. This will also ease the
communication between the user interface and the data layer.

By using a simple wrapper around SharedPreferences for each of the
available preference we have a clean and simple interface to work with.

title: Add a new menu for the `ProjectActivity`
message:
Add a new menu for the `ProjectActivity`

To enable hiding registered time via a toggle menu, a new menu for the
`ProjectActivity` have been created.

title: Rename the menu for timesheet actions
message:
Rename the menu for timesheet actions

The `actions_project.xml` will be reused for actual menu items related
to the `ProjectActivity` and not fragment.

message: Compile with Java 7

message: Add scheme for automatic backup

title: Confirm before deleting registered time
message:
Confirm before deleting registered time

Since the mark as time as registered and the delete buttons are fairly
close, and the delete is a destructive action, the user have to confirm
the action.

Before calling `TimesheetPresenter::remove(TimeInAdapterResult)` an
alert dialog is requesting the users confirmation.

title: Remove usage of private resource
message: Remove usage of private resource

title: Handle usage of fragment `onAttach(Activity)`
message:
Handle usage of fragment `onAttach(Activity)`

Since API 23 the method `onAttach(Activity)` has been marked as
deprecated, instead the `onAttach(Context)` method should be used.

Since we are supporting API 21 we need to support both methods. By
using a single `setup`-method code duplication is reduced.

In API 23, `onAttach(Activity)` method is still called from
`onAttach(Context)` we have to handle this within `onAttach(Activity)`,
i.e. do not setup the fragment twice.

I'm unsure of how long the deprecated method will be called, it might
be removed in future version, we should not depend on this behaviour.

title: Suppress warning of inverted boolean
message:
Suppress warning of inverted boolean

The inspect code complains about 'Boolean method is always inverted'
for the methods `isViewAttached` and `has`.

The method names have been chosen because it better defines the flow
of the code than the negative counterpart, i.e. `isViewNotAttached`
and `hasNot`. Also, the shorter method name is preferred.

The warning have been suppressed with annotation.

title: Replace usage of deprecated method call
message:
Replace usage of deprecated method call

The `setOnScrollListener(OnScrollListener)` method have been deprecated
and should be replaced with `addOnScrollListener(OnScrollListener)`.

title: Replace usage of deprecated method call
message:
Replace usage of deprecated method call

The `getDrawable(int)` method have been deprecated since API 16 and
since we've updated the level to API 21 we can replace the method call
with the supported version, i.e. `getDrawable(int, Theme)`.

title: Remove ambiguous drawable declaration
message:
Remove ambiguous drawable declaration

By statically importing the drawable the ambiguity disappear.

title: Fix nullable warning
message:
Fix nullable warning

Since `getClockedInSince` is used and is nullable, we should check for
a valid value instead of checking `isActive`.

In this context they should be interchangable since `getClockedInSince`
will only return a value if the project is active.

title: Update the minimum SDK version to lollipop
message:
Update the minimum SDK version to lollipop

Since everybody using the application have at least API +22, there is
no reason to support any lower APIs.

This also reduces the level of work that's needed to maintain backward
compatibility, i.e. more focus on new features and cleaner code with
ability to use JDK 7.

title: Timesheet group fails to mark as registered
message:
Timesheet group fails to mark as registered

When the timesheet view have multiple expanded groups, and the user
marks the last unregistered item the group fails to be marked as
registered. If the group is any other than the first group.

The issue is related to the internal position system of the expandable
list adapter. I.e. the group position do not always match to the
correct adapter position, since its offset by child items.

title: Display group registered status based on children
message:
Display group registered status based on children

If the child items within the group have all been registered the group should
be considered registered and display the same background color.

title: Restore activated state with action mode dismiss
message:
Restore activated state with action mode dismiss

If the action mode is dismissed without any performed action, the
activated state of the selected item have to be restored.

title: Restore activated state when selecting a new item
message:
Restore activated state when selecting a new item

If an item is selected, we have to restore the activated state of the
previously selected item, if one is available. Otherwise, the activated
state will be out of sync with the data.

title: Deactivate selected view
message:
Deactivate selected view

Regardless of the registered status of the time, its view should be
deactivated since the selected background color should take precedence
of the activated.

title: Display time marked as registered
message:
Display time marked as registered

Display the time marked as registered with a green background color.
The color seemed as a logical choice, green as in completed.

The current implementation relies on activating the view when the time
have been marked as registered.

This approach is not optimal since activating do not seem logical, but
the states available for the default view is somewhat limited.

title: Mark time as registered
message:
Mark time as registered

Enable support for marking time as registered in a external system.

title: Update item within TimeInAdapterResult
message:
Update item within TimeInAdapterResult

Enabled support for updating item stored in the TimeInAdapterResult.
The group and child positions should not be updatable since they
represent a valid location within a data structure. And, the data
stored in the location is allowed to be changed.

message:
Update expandable child item

Implemented support for updating a single child item within the data of
the ExpandableListAdapter. The update trigger an update to the group.

title: Throw exception if clock in after clock out
message:
Throw exception if clock in after clock out

Since we can't allow to clock out before clock in, we should not
allow clock in after clock out. I've added additional checks with
unit tests to verify this behaviour.

title: Added default value for start
message:
Added default value for start

Since the start value have been converted to a Long from long,
getting the value and comparing it before initialization will
throw a NullPointerException. With the use of a default value
we do not have this problem.

title: Update unit test for Time domain model
message:
Update unit test for Time domain model

I've updated the unit tests for the Time domain model. Most of the
changes are not to the actual unit test but the structure around them.

The major points of the structural changes are as follows.

Renamed the test methods. Previously, I was inconsistent about naming
the methods, so I've tried to some degree to adapt the names to a new
naming convention, "MethodName_StateUnderTest_ExpectedBehaviour".

Rearranged methods in order of expected behaviour, you have to fail
before you can succeed.

title: Use object wrapper instead of primitive for Time
message:
Use object wrapper instead of primitive for Time

Replaced the use of the long primitive with the Long object wrapper to
be consistent with the rest of the domain layer.

Also, removed unnecessary boxing within the ProjectTest.

title: Update unit test for Project domain model
message:
Update unit test for Project domain model

I've updated the unit tests for the Project domain model. Most of the
changes is not to the actual unit test but the structure around them.

The major points of the structural changes are as follows.

Renamed the test methods. Previously, I was inconsistent about naming
the methods, so I've tried to some degree to adapt the names to a new
naming convention, "MethodName_StateUnderTest_ExpectedBehaviour".

Rearranged methods in order of expected behaviour, you have to fail
before you can succeed.

Changed all primitive data types to their respective object wrappers.
The reason for this is, the domain models should work with objects and
not primitives where possible.

I've also added some additional tests for cases I've missed before and
tweaked some tests to be more consistent.

message:
Redesigned the interaction between activity and fragment when creating new project.

I've redesigned the interaction between the MainActivity and
ProjectsFragment when creating new projects. This is done by
dispatching the create event to the fragment and let it deal
with the dialog and adapter update.

Also, it makes the connection between the activity and fragment
a bit more loosely coupled since the dependencies have been
reduced and only relys on an interface.

DateTimePickerFragment - Initialize clean up on cancel or dismiss.

The date picker only initialize the clean up if it is cancelled
because we still need the DateTimePickerFragment when a date have
been selected, i.e. the date picker is dismissed.

The time picker however needs to initialize the clean up when
it's dismissed, since it doesn't matter why it was dismissed.
